<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Mongolia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Legislator Found Guilty of Violating Constitution </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1301163194 Ulaanbaatar MONTSAME in English 1510 GMT 13 Jan 
94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1301163194 </F>
<F P=104>  Ulaanbaatar MONTSAME </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Ulaanbaatar, January 13 (OANA-MONTSAME) -- The 
Constitutional Court of Mongolia has established the breach of 
the constitutional provision committed by a member of the 
Mongolian Parliament T. Turmandah. According to the 
Constitutional Court, the member of the Great State Hural has 
violated Article 29 of the Constitution of Mongolia which 
prohibits members of the Parliament to be engaged in activities 
which are not referring to those prescribed by the law. By 
taking this decision the court has met the complaints of a 
number of Mongolian citizen, all the delegates of the opposition 
in the parliament concerning the actions of T. Turmandah being 
engaged in commercial business as a director of the independent 
television broadcasting company MCHT-1. 
  T. Turmandah became the first member of a new parliament of 
Mongolia to have committed the breach of the legislation of the 
country for a period of year and a half of its activities. 

</TEXT>

