<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Top Tokyo, U.S. Military Discuss DPRK Nuclear Issue </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1401021594 Tokyo KYODO in English 0153 GMT 14 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1401021594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Washington, Jan. 13 KYODO -- Top Japanse and U.S. 
military leaders discussed North Korea's alleged nuclear arms 
development program as they met in Washington Thursday [13 
January], a visiting top Japanese military leader said. 
  Gen. Tetsuya Nishimoto, chairman of the Joint Staff Council 
of Japan's Self-Defense Forces, paid a courtesy call on Gen. 
John Shalikashvili, chairman of the U.S. joint chiefs of staff, 
at the Pentagon. 
  Nishimoto later told reporters that he discussed North 
Korea's nuclear program and other matters with Shalikashvili, 
and got the impression that "the U.S. has been negotiating very 
patiently" with Pyongyang over the nuclear issue. 
  The United States is formulating a comprehensive policy 
approach toward North Korea that focuses not only on the nuclear 
issue but also takes into account North Korea's missile 
development program, its vast military power and possible 
involvement in international terrorism, he said. 
  Nishimoto is currently on a three-day visit to the United 
States as Shalikashvili's official guest. 

</TEXT>

