<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Police Probe Military-Related Export to DPRK </TI></H3>
<H4>   Kanagawa Trading Firm Suspected </H4>
<F P=102> OW1401022294 Tokyo KYODO in English 0138 GMT 14 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1401022294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 14 KYODO -- The Tokyo Metropolitan 
Police Department on Friday [14 January] launched a probe into 
the suspected export of a military-related, high-tech device to 
North Korea, police sources said. 
  Police suspect a Kanagawa Prefecture-based trading company, 
specializing in deals between Tokyo and Pyongyang, exported a 
spectrum analyzer which can be converted to military use. 
  Export of the device is regulated by the Paris-based 
Coordinating Committee for Multilateral Export Controls (Cocom), 
which tries to control the sale of strategically important goods 
to communist countries. 
  The spectrum analyzer can be used to improve the aiming 
precision of weapons, authorities said. 
  Police also suspect the trading firm applied to the Ministry 
of International Trade and Industry for permission to export the 
analyzer using false information, the sources said. 
  Although the device was allegedly exported to Pyongyang by 
the Kanagawa-based trading firm, the Tokyo-based maker of the 
device was not informed to which country the analyzer would be 
sent, police added. 
  The manufacturer was also not told for what purpose the 
analyzer would be used, the sources said. 
  They did not identify either the manufacturer or the trading 
firm. 
  The sources said police will question persons concerned for 
alleged violation of foreign exchange and foreign trade control 
law. 
  The YOMIURI SHIMBUN reported Friday that North Korea may use 
the analyzer for development of the intermediate-range missile 
called "Nodong-1." 
  The national daily said the spectrum analyzer is able to 
measure more precisely the distance between a missile launcher 
and a target by analyzing the rebounding of a radar beam. 
  North Korea last May successfully test-launched a Nodong-1 
missile, which has an estimated range of 1,000 kilometers. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

