<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hata Welcomes Outcome of Clinton-Yeltsin Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1401025294 Tokyo KYODO in English 0230 GMT 14 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1401025294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 14 KYODO -- Japan welcomes the outcome 
of the summit talks between U.S. President Bill Clinton and 
Russian President Boris Yeltsin, Foreign Minister Tsutomu Hata 
said Friday [14 Janaury]. 
  Yeltsin pledged to press on with democratic reforms in 
Russia 
while Clinton reconfirmed continued support for the Russian 
efforts, Hata told a news conference. 
  Japan will also continue to back Russian reform efforts in 
cooperation with other Group of Seven (G-7) industrialized 
nations, Hata said. 
  He also gave high marks to the scheduled signing of an 
agreement among the U.S., Russia and Ukraine which is expected 
to pave the way for Kiev to scrap nuclear missiles, saying the 
accord would contribute to the world's security and that Japan 
will continue to cooperate in it. 
  Clinton and Yeltsin are due to sign the historic accord with 
Ukrainian leader Leonid Kravchuk later in the day. 

</TEXT>

