<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Talks Cut Trans-Siberia Flight Delays From Tokyo </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1301135994 Tokyo KYODO in English 1028 GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1301135994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 13 KYODO -- Talks between the 
Transport Ministry and Russian aviation authorities have reduced 
delays to Europe-bound flights using Siberian air space after 
several weeks of long delays imposed by the Russian side, 
Japanese officials said Thursday [13 January]. 
  Russia imposed restrictions on flights over Siberia late 
last 
year causing hefty delays for many Europe-bound passenger 
flights from Japan and South Korea. 
  Airlines experienced delays of over an hour to their 
scheduled departures from Narita Airport. 
  Russian aviation authorities said the flight restrictions, 
sent as a formal "notice to airmen" on December 28, were a 
safety measure following a deterioration in the reliability of 
radio communications equipment and would last until March 27. 
  The restrictions limited the number of civilian flights out 
of Japan and passing near Khabarovsk to a maximum of six flights 
per hour, one-third of the previous frequency. 
  Between 40 and 50 flights use this route into and out of 
Narita each day but each was obliged to await clearance from 
Russian authorities even if all passengers were on board. 
  As a result of the negotiations, the restrictions were eased 
from January 7, allowing six flights per hour from Narita alone 
and resulting in a 50 percent reduction in the average delay to 
between 30 minutes and one hour. 

</TEXT>

