<H3> <TI>   Hosokawa Notes Plans To Visit China in Mar </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1401090994 Tokyo KYODO in English 0857 GMT 14 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1401090994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 14 KYODO -- Prime Minister Morihiro 
Hosokawa on Friday [14 January] indicated his intention to visit 
China in late March for talks with Chinese leaders on bilateral 
and international issues. 
  Hosokawa made remarks to this effect in a meeting with a 
group of reporters at his official residence. 
  Asked about his travel plans following his visit to the 
United States in February to meet President Bill Clinton, 
Hosokawa said he has no alternative but to visit Japan's 
"neighboring country," taken to mean China because the premier 
visited South Korea last November. 
  In reply to a question on the timing of his possible visit, 
Hosokawa indicated it would be around March 21. 

</TEXT>

