<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tokyo To Host Vietnamese Trade Exposition </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1301133994 Tokyo KYODO in English 0859 GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1301133994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 13 KYODO -- A major Vietnamese trade 
exposition, the first of its kind ever held in Japan, will open 
in Tokyo on January 19, officials of the Japan External Trade 
Organization (JETRO) said Thursday [13 January]. 
  Officials said the exposition, aimed at enhancing trade ties 
between the two countries, will be sponsored by Jetro and the 
Vietnam Chamber of Commerce and Industry and supported by both 
the Japanese and Vietnamese Governments. 
  It will last through January 27 and precede the holding of a 
Japanese industrial product trade fair in Hanoi next March. 
  Representatives from 25 Vietnamese companies will be 
exhibiting such potential export items as marine products, 
coffee, handicrafts, furniture and clothing. 
  According to Finance Ministry figures, Vietnamese exports to 
Japan have skyrocketed in recent years, from 196 million dollars 
in 1988 to 870 million dollars in 1992. 
  Vietnam had a whopping trade surplus with Japan of 419 
million dollars in 1992. Mineral fuels accounted for 62.2 
percent of Japanese imports from Vietnam in that year, followed 
by foodstuffs and industrial products. 

</TEXT>

