<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   MOF Says Tokyo Likely To Resume Loans to Cambodia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1301132494 Tokyo KYODO in English 1013 GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1301132494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 13 KYODO -- Japan is likely to resume 
extending official yen loans to Cambodia as early as this year 
after nearly 25 years of suspension, Foreign Ministry [MOF] 
sources said Thursday [13 January]. 
  The Japanese Government plans to provide the loans in 
cooperation with the World Bank to ease Cambodia's international 
balance of payments problem, the sources said. 
  The amount of the loans, however, remains undetermined, they 
said. 
  Japan last extended a 1.5 billion yen loan in March 1969. 
  The government is likely to decide on resumption of the 
loans 
after the International Monetary Fund (IMF) assesses the 
Cambodian economy in February, they said. 
  It is not clear whether Tokyo will be able to make an 
announcement on the new loans at the International Committee on 
the Reconstruction of Cambodia (ICORC) scheduled to be held in 
March, because a meeting of Paris Club creditor nations is to be 
held in April, the sources said. 
  The ICORC was set up in June 1992 at a ministerial meeting. 
At its first meeting in Paris last September, donor nations 
pledged 119 million dollars in new aid in addition to the 880 
million dollars pledged at the ministerial meeting. 
  Cambodia is estimated to owe Japan some 2.6 billion yen. The 
accumulated debt is an obstacle to Japan's resumption of yen 
loans. 
  Japan has been offering Cambodia grant-in-aids for projects 
to improve the war-torn country's infrastructure. Japan 
extended 6.12 billion yen in fiscal 1992 and 8 billion yen in 
fiscal 1993. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

