<H3> <TI>   Condolences Offered to Norway on Holst's Death </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1401062394 Tokyo KYODO in English 0609 GMT 14 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1401062394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 15 KYODO -- The Japanese Government on 
Friday [14 January] offered its condolences to Norway over the 
sudden death of Foreign Minister Johan Holst on Thursday and 
said it will send telegrams expressing its sympathy. 
  The death of Holst, who played a pivotal role in the Middle 
East peace process, was "a great shock," said Foreign Ministry 
spokesman Sadaaki Numata, adding it is a loss not only for 
Norway but the whole world. 
  Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa, Foreign Minister Tsutomu 
Hata and other Japanese Government officials will send telegrams 
of condolence later in the day, the spokesman said. 
  Holst, 56, who was instrumental in brokering the historic 
agreement between Israel and the Palestine Liberation 
Organization (PLO) last Septmeber for limited Palestinian 
self-rule in the occupied territories, died after reportedly 
suffering a stroke. 
  He visited Japan last October and held talks with Hosokawa 
and Hata. 

</TEXT>

