<H3> <TI>   EPA Notes Possible Delay in Stimulus Package </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1401022494 Tokyo KYODO in English 0159 GMT 14 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1401022494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 14 KYODO -- Japan's chief economic 
planner Friday [14 January] hinted at a "little" delay in 
releasing the government's additional economic stimulus package 
originally expected January 20. 
  "I can't deny the possibility of a little delay," Manae 
Kubota, director general of the Economic Planning Agency [EPA] 
told reporters after the regular morning cabinet meeting. 
  Her agency is working on the package as instructed by Prime 
Minister Morihiro Hosokawa for compilation by "mid-January," 
Kubota said. 
  But she indicated the chances of delay while citing the need 
for further discussion among coalition parties and some 
uncertainties still remaining over political reform, Hosokawa's 
previously stated "top priority" for his administration. 
  Kubota said there were no questions or comments over the 
stimulus measures at the cabinet meeting. 
  Meanwhile, the Economic Planning Agency chief quoted Bank of 
Japan Governor Yasushi Mieno as saying that the recent rally in 
Japanese stock prices stems from "bargain-hunting" against 
strongly rising overseas stocks. 
  Mieno was speaking at a meeting of economic ministers held 
before the cabinet meeting. 
  On the dollar-yen exchange rates, Mieno stressed the dollar 
has recovered "half" of its losses against the yen since January 
last year with the weakening of the yen since December to the 
range of 110 to 112 yen to the dollar, Kubota said. 
  She also quoted Mieno as saying that interest rates have 
fallen to record levels, but bank lending has remained sluggish. 

</TEXT>

