<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   EPA Official Calls Economic Situation `Severe' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1401000994 Tokyo KYODO in English 2355 GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1401000994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 14 KYODO -- Japan's economy continues 
to wade through its worst stage of recession, the evidence of 
which can be seen in many areas, the Economic Planning Agency 
(EPA) said in a monthly report Friday [14 January]. 
  An agency official briefing reporters on the monthly report 
on the state of Japanese economy said the situation is severe 
and the recession is lagging on. 
  In the report, the EPA simply stated that the state of the 
economy is "overall sluggish." 
  Asked if the agency is using its gloomiest words possible to 
describe the situation, the official answered "yes." 
  The EPA pointed out that consumer spending remained 
lackluster, while the weakness of plant and equipment investment 
is spreading from manufacturers to the nonmanufacturing sector. 
  The report noted the plodding process of inventory 
adjustments and said industrial output remains stagnant. 
  The official said business conditions of private enterprises 
are worsening. He said he can no longer attribute the situation 
merely to the yen's appreciation, admitting the overall 
situation is simply "bad." 
  Job offers continued to decline, while the unemployment rate 
continues to increase, the report said. 
  The EPA said the government is hence currently working to 
compile another comprehensive pump-priming package to spur the 
economy, in addition to steady implementation of past 
stimulation programs. 
  Exports are down with effects of the yen's appreciation 
gradually appearing and because of an adjustment of the economic 
growth in China after a heated period, the official said. 
  Meanwhile, implementation of public works spending improved 
and housing starts were also solid. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

