<H3> <TI>   Finance Minister Says Draft Budget Not Yet Set </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1401023094 Tokyo KYODO in English 0157 GMT 14 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1401023094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 14 KYODO -- Finance Minister Hirohisa 
Fujii on Friday [14 January] denied reports that the Finance 
Ministry will compile a draft budget for fiscal 1994 on February 
5. 
  Speaking at a regularly scheduled news conference, Fujii 
said 
he has not heard about a specific schedule for next year's 
national budget. 
  Major newspapers reported the ruling coalition parties, at 
Thursday's meeting of their leaders in charge of policy affairs, 
decided to announce a tax reform plan for next year on February 
3 and the Finance Ministry's draft budget two days later. 
  The ministry wants to begin compiling the next year's budget 
"as soon as possible" while closely watching developments in 
Diet debate over political reform bills, Fujii said. 
  Fujii denied the United States has proposed holding a 
ministerial meeting as a way to break through stalled 
"framework" trade talks with Japan. 
  The comment came after U.S. Trade Representative Mickey 
Kantor on Wednesday recommended holding such a meeting between 
the two countries before U.S. President Bill Clinton and 
Japanese Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa meet in Washington on 
February 11. 

</TEXT>

