<H3> <TI>   NEC Boosts Magneto-Optical Disk Capacity </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1301140194 Tokyo KYODO in English 1022 GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1301140194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 13 KYODO -- NEC Corp. said Thursday 
[13 January] it has developed a technique to enhance the memory 
capacity of a magneto-optical disc by eight times as much as the 
current method. 
  The technique makes it possible to store data equivalent to 
some 80,000 Japanese newspaper pages or two hours of VHS-format 
video movie pictures on a magneto-optical disc which measures 13 
centimeters in diameter, the same size as a music disc, the 
company said. 
  A magneto-optical disc is based on a recording method that 
combines laser and magnetic technologies to create high-density 
erasable storage discs. Its surface is made of a magnetic 
recording material that records magnetic spots or bits using a 
laser to pinpoint them. 
  NEC's new technique combines a signal-processing technology 
called the partial response maximum likelihood (prml) method 
with a red-color data-reading laser. 
  NEC said it plans to develop products using the technique 
for 
commercial use as it can be applied to a range of multimedia 
equipment. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-47582 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas010_a_94026" </HT>


