<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Panel Urges Employment Help for Older Workers </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1401093594 Tokyo KYODO in English 0842 GMT 14 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1401093594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 14 KYODO -- A Labor Ministry advisory 
panel urged the government Friday [14 January] to ease 
restrictions on private agencies that supply temporary labor so 
as to provide wider job opportunities for workers aged 60 years 
or over, ministry officials said. 
  The officials said the appeal was contained in a report 
submitted to Labor Minister Chikara Sakaguchi by the Central 
Employment Security Council. 
  The report called for widening the scope of job categories 
from the current 16, including secretaries and interpreters, 
that such agencies are allowed to handle. 
  The report also called on the government to provide 
subsidies 
to corporations which improve working conditions for senior 
workers. 
  The recommendations include a call for the establishment of 
a 
center to help workers over 60 find jobs, the officials said. 
  They said the ministry plans to submit to the next ordinary 
session of the Diet a bill to revise a job security law to 
incorporate the proposed measures and make it mandatory for 
corporations to set the retirement age at 60 in principle. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

