<F P=100> Brunei, Malaysia &amp; Singapore </F>
<F P=101> Malaysia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Badawi: Singapore `Committed' to EAEC </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK1401110794 Kuala Lumpur BERNAMA in English 0929 GMT 14 Jan 
94 </F>

<F P=103> BK1401110794 </F>
<F P=104>  Kuala Lumpur BERNAMA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Kuala Lumpur, Jan 14 (OANA-BERNAMA) -- Malaysia and 
Singapore Friday agreed to expedite efforts to realise the East 
Asia Economic Caucus (EAEC), and they did not rule out the 
possibility of seeing the caucus formed this year, Foreign 
Minister Abdullah Haji Ahmad Badawi said Friday. 
  He said Singapore, a party committed to the concept, 
understood the need to realise the caucus in the very near 
future in the light of the conducive atmosphere both inside and 
outside the region. 
  Obstacles are no longer there, more so with the change of 
Washington's stand (on the matter) and that of Tokyo's, he told 
reporters after a 90-minute meeting with Singapore Foreign 
Minister Professor S. Jayakumar who arrived here this morning on 
his first visit to Malaysia. 
  We like to see EAEC taking shape this year itself, he said, 
adding that the ASEAN Secretariat in Jakarta was working towards 
it. 
  He said Prof. Jayakumar agreed that given the present 
circumstances, there was no reason for the caucus not to be 
realised soon. 
  Abdullah said he hoped that the working relationship between 
Kuala Lumpur and Singapore need not be too formal and that the 
cordial ties should also be enhanced down the line, especially 
at the officials level. Being neighbours, Ablullah said, a 
good relationship between the officials was vital to further 
maintain the long-standing bilateral ties. 

</TEXT>

