<F P=100> Cambodia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Thai Premier on Investment For `Mutual Interest' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK1401014994 Bangkok BANGKOK POST in English 14 Jan 94 p 19 </F>
<F P=103> BK1401014994 </F>
<F P=104>  Bangkok BANGKOK POST </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Prime Minister Chuan Likphai says foreign 
investors should steer clear of short-term ventures that unduly 
exploit Cambodians. 
  "Investment should be based on mutual interest with no 
exploitation and it must be in line with the direction and the 
interests of the people who own the country," he told more than 
200 Cambodian officials and Thai businessmen at a seminar on 
investment in Cambodia. 
  The seminar, entitled New Dimension of Cambodia's Investment 
and Environment, is organised by the Board of Investment and the 
Thai Embassy. It is the first major seminar since the formation 
of the elected Cambodian Government. [passage omitted] 
  Mr Chuan, accompanied by a large delegation of public and 
private sector officials, arrived on Wednesday for what embassy 
officials called an "historic visit" aimed at boosting the often 
troubled relations between the two neighbouring kingdoms. 
  The visit was to focus primarily on trade, which the premier 
said had "expanded rapidly from around $600,000 in 1988 to $183 
million in the first half of 1993". [passage omitted] 
  He said more than 10,000 million baht had been invested by 
Thais in Cambodia and this showed they had great interest in 
Cambodia. [passage omitted] 
  "We want to see the good investors drive out the bad." 
  The deputy governor of the National Bank of Cambodia said 
the 
Khmer Government did not control money transfers and foreigners 
were free to transfer their profits. 
  Companies have to pay 20-30 percent income tax. The 
Government will waive it for four years starting from when the 
company makes a profit and waive import duty on materials and 
machinery for export- oriented projects. 
  Federation of Thai Industries president Chokchai Aksaranan 
called on the Cambodian Government to have a clear-cut policy on 
trade and investment. 
  "The policy must be clear and transparent and must not be 
changed so often," he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

