<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Expert: U.S.-North Accord `Emboldens' Kim Il-song </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1401024894 Seoul YONHAP in English 0230 GMT 14 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1401024894 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Washington, Jan. 13 (YONHAP) -- The Clinton 
administration's willingness to accept North Korea's offer of a 
one- time inspection of seven out of nine identified nuclear 
sites only emboldens North Korean leader Kim Il-song, a 
conservative think-tank said Thursday [13 January]. 
  The U.S. Government's agreement with North Korea on the 
nuclear inspection leaves America's Asian allies wondering 
whether U.S. security assurances are reliable, Seth Cropsey, the 
director of the Heritage Foundation's Asian Studies Center, said. 
  The Clinton administration should make no more concessions 
at 
the negotiating table, Cropsey said. 
  Instead, it should inform North Korea that if it does not 
allow full international inspections of all its nuclear sites on 
a regular basis by Feb. 1, the United States will ask the U.N. 
Security Council for economic sanctions the following day, he 
said. 
  The Clinton administration has already erred by postponing a 
diplomatic confrontation in the U.N. Security Council, where the 
issue of sanctions against the Kim regime should be raised, 
Cropsey said. 
  "North Korea now realizes President Bill Clinton suffers 
from 
lack of nerve, yielding to the apparent implacability of an 
armed tyrant demonstrates vulnerability," Cropsey said. 
  "It can only lead to more North Korean evasion, excuses, 
delaying tactics and in the end aggression -- perhaps nuclear 
aggression." 
  Even worse, he said, "By placing two North Korean nuclear 
sites beyond the reach of international inspectors, the 
compromise leaves the way open for Kim to continue his 
weapons-building program." 
  The compromise also abandons Washington's reasonable 
expectations that North Korea will allow regular inspections as 
set forth in the Nuclear Nonproliferation Treaty, he said. 
  Cropsey, a former high-ranking U.S. Defense Ministry 
official, recommended that the United States seize the 
initiative in Asia with a number of bold steps. They include: 
  -- Lift the trade embargo against Vietnam to demonstrate to 
North Korea that Americans are magnanimous to former foes. 
  -- Increase pressure on Japan to reduce the flow of funds -- 
at least 600 million U.S. dollars a year -- from Korean 
residents in Japan who send desperately needed hard currency to 
North Korea. 
  -- Promise more favorable terms to China as a means to 
enlist 
Beijing's help in putting economic pressure on Pyongyang. 
  -- Hold a naval military exercise in the western Pacific to 
remind Kim Il-song how quickly America can move military forces 
over a long distance. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-47622 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas010_d_94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-010 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  14 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

