<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Study of Transport Networks Planned With PRC </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1401012994 Seoul YONHAP in English 0101 GMT 14 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1401012994 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Jan. 14 (YONHAP) -- The Korea Maritime 
Institute (KMI) said Friday it has accepted a proposal by the 
Chinese State Planning Commission's Institute of Comprehensive 
Transportation for a joint study of traffic and transportation 
in Northeast Asia. 
  Experts from the two institutes will discuss details of the 
study of transportation of cargo between South Korea and China 
and developing transportation networks in inland China in 
Beijing this month. 
  Effective transportation by air, sea and land between the 
two 
countries, and the development of a better transportation system 
in China are the aims. 
  China will hand necessary materials to KMI, which will share 
the experience that Korea has with economic development since 
the 1960s. 
  Seoul has a deep interests in expanding the shipment of 
cargo 
to Europe via the trans-China railroad and in building a rail 
link between Korea and China after unification of the Korean 
peninsula. 
  Korean and Chinese experts agree that a satisfactory traffic 
system does not exist in Northeast Asia, unlike Europe, so a 
joint study is necessary, KMI researcher Chong Pil-su said, and 
the joint study on traffic between Korea and China should be 
expanded to all Northeast Asia. 
  The Institute of Comprehensive Transportation, built in 
1959, 
is the largest transportation research institute in China and 
has nearly 100 researchers. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

