<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Korea Telecom, Indonesian Firm Sign Accord </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1401100794 Seoul YONHAP in English 0747 GMT 14 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1401100794 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Jan. 14 (YONHAP) -- Korea Telecom and Indosat 
Co., an Indonesian communications firm, have signed an agreement 
on joint projects, a company spokesman said Friday. 
  Telecom President Cho Paek-che and Indosat President 
Tjahjono 
Soerjodibroto signed the agreement at a Pacific partners' 
meeting in Hawaii. 
  They will form a consortium to participate in an 
international tender to be placed by the Indonesian Government 
for installing 2 million telephone lines on a build, operate and 
transfer (BOF) basis. 
  Under its sixth economic development plan, the Indonesian 
Government plans to install 5 million lines. 
  Developing countries prefer BOF, by which foreign firms 
operate invested facilities for a time and hand them over after 
gaining a preset profit. 
  If the consortium succeeds, it will help build Korea 
Telecom's reputation in the area, the spokesman said. 
  Telecom has consulted on two projects in Indonesia. One on 
communication technology at 3.9 million U.S. dollars and the 
other on building a communications network at 1.3 million 
dollars. 

</TEXT>

