<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Exporters Fear `Setbacks' Due to NAFTA </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1301133294 Seoul YONHAP in English 1048 GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1301133294 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Jan. 13 (YONHAP) -- The half of major South 
Korean export companies fear they would suffer setbacks in 
exports to the United States due to the effectuation of the 
North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA). 
  The Korea Trade Promotion Corp. (KOTRA) reported on Thursday 
a survey it recently held of 150 leading export firms showed 
that 75 firms, just half of the companies surveyed, said they 
fear their exports would be adversely affected by the NAFTA. 
  Only 19 firms or 12.7 percent of the total said they expect 
no impact at all. On the other hand, 13 companies (8.7 percent) 
said they believe NAFTA would have a favorable effect on their 
exports. 
  As major factors behind negative effect, 69.6 percent of the 
firms questioned gave tariff removal among three NAFTA 
countries, 25.6 percent "country of origin" rules, and 4.8 
percent the opening of investment and service. 
  Of the firms surveyed, 30.1 percent replied they believe the 
country's exports would decline by 1-5 percent due to NAFTA, 
28.2 percent by 5-10 percent, and 19.4 percent by more than 10 
percent. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

