<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   President Gives Directives to Labor, Communications </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1301060894 Seoul YONHAP in English 0517 GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1301060894 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Jan. 13 (YONHAP) -- South Korea needs stable 
industrial relations if it is to become an advanced country, 
President Kim Yong-sam said Thursday after he received a report 
from the Labor Ministry at Chongwadae [presidential office]. 
  Kim told the Labor Ministry to do its best to make this year 
the first year of labor-management cooperation" and make efforts 
to keep the peace in industrial relations and encourage low wage 
demands. 
  "Pay raises reached 12 percent in stagnation last year. This 
pace of increase will weaken the competitiveness of industry," 
Kim said. 
  The ministry should see to it that unions obey the law when 
they exercise their rights and encourage district labor 
administration offices to do their best to prevent industrial 
disputes, Kim said. 
  It should also study the welfare of workers, including the 
expansion of stock-sharing for employees and of housing for 
workers, he said. 
  Preventing industrial accidents is important because of 
respect for human life and stabilization of occupation, he said. 
  "Enterprisers should have the mind that they are putting 
their own children to work," the president said. 
  In a separate briefing session later in the day, Kim 
instructed the Communications Ministry to make creation of a 
super high speed information network, the communications system 
of the future, its top priority project in 1994. 
  "Carry out the matters of primary concern, including selling 
stocks of communications businesses and selection of the 
business that will take the second cellular phone project justly 
and without any suspicion," he ordered. 
  He instructed the ministry to internationalize the 
communications industry and privatise communications companies 
to introduce competition in the field, most of which is 
currently state- controlled. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

