<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Strike-Ridden Firms To Lose State Support </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1301034194 Seoul YONHAP in English 0215 GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1301034194 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Jan. 13 (YONHAP) -- Companies with a history 
of bad labor relations will be discriminated against in the 
doling out of state support as punishment for breaking 
industrial peace under a policy being drawn up by the Labor 
Ministry in consultation with other ministries, Labor Minister 
Nam Chae-hui told President Kim Yong-sam in a briefing on his 
Ministry's new year operating program Thursday. 
  Noting that labor relations at three strike-plagued Hyundai 
Group Companies -- Hyundai Motor, Hyundai Precision and 
Industries and Hyundai Heavy Industries -- in 1993 are being 
examined by the Korea Labor Research Institute, Nam said the 
government would see to it that they improved their labor 
relations on the basis of the recommendations to be made by the 
institute. 
  Companies in four booming sectors -- automobiles, 
shipbuilding, steel and electronics -- will be encouraged to pay 
special bonuses from their profits in shares, not in cash. 
  Easing of rules barring employees from selling shares 
obtained in employee stock ownership plans for five years is 
being discussed with the Finance Ministry, Nam said. 
  Under the proposed changes, the ban will be shortened so 
that 
employees in the four sectors may sell their shares after a year. 
  The four sectors will be induced to peg pay hikes at the 
level set by wage guidelines to be agreed on between the 
Federation of Korean Trade Unions (FKTU) and the Korea 
Employers' Federation (KEF) and to invest their profits in 
research and development and expansion of welfare facilities for 
employees. 
  The government will ensure that collective pay bargaining is 
finished according to the FKTU-KEF guidelines by April or May in 
all industrial sectors. 
  Nam recommended that Kim call a government-labor-management 
meeting to celebrate and promote industrial peace after 
collective bargaining is completed. 
  He said his Ministry would study when and how labor-related 
laws should be amended after pay negotiations are settled in all 
areas. 
  Illegal labor disputes, especially involvement of a third 
party in a labor dispute, will be dealt with strictly by law, 
Nam said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

