<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Measures To Stabilize Stock Market Prepared </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1401062294 Seoul YONHAP in English 0609 GMT 14 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1401062294 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Jan. 14 (YONHAP) -- Prices crashed on the 
Korea stock exchange on Friday after the government announced 
that it was preparing measures to take some of the heat out of 
the market. 
  The all-share composite stock price index was nearing 900 
points on a three-day rebound when the announcement that the 
government wanted prices to drop sent it nosediving 15.85 points 
to 882.81 as of 2:15 p.m. 
  It had diagnosed signs of overheating in the market, the 
government said, and so decided to cool things off by letting 
securities companies lend shares, making institutional investors 
put down deposits on stock like small investors, and encouraging 
banks and other financial institutions not to buy shares. This 
is to take effect on Monday. 
  There was little change on the surface at first as the flood 
of sell offers generated by the rebirth of share loans and 
selling by the stock stabilization fund was absorbed, but the 
selling got the upper hand toward the end of the morning session. 
  Just a few high PER (price/earnings ratio) shares such as 
Taekwang Industrial Co. and large manufacturing issues such as 
Pohang Iron and Steel Co. and Samsung Electronics Co. rose by 
the daily ceiling. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

