<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Commodity Exports Reach $102 Million in Final Quarter </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1301013394 Seoul YONHAP in English 0109 GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1301013394 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Jan. 13 (YONHAP) -- South Korea exported 280 
strategic commodities for 102,285,000 U.S. dollars in the final 
quarter of 1993, the Trade, Industry and Energy Ministry said 
Thursday. 
  Korea joined the Coordinating Committee for Multilateral 
Export Controls (COCOM) in October after establishing a system 
according to a memorandum of understanding on exports of 
strategic commodities and technical data signed in September 
1987. 
  The exports comprised 100,912,000 dollars of 
telecommunications equipment, including computers, 963,000 
dollars of machinery, including navigation systems, and 410,000 
dollars of materials, including carbon fiber. 
  Exports to former or current communist countries, including 
China, Poland, Russia, Vietnam and Hungary, were less than 19.8 
million dollars, or 19.4 percent of the total. The remaining 
exports of strategic goods were to Singapore, Germany, Malaysia, 
Hong Kong, the United States and Taiwan. 
  Import certificates issued by the government reached 1,962 
million dollars. 
  The certificates are promises by a company not to export 
strategic items that it has purchased, and must be sent to the 
seller before he can ship the goods. 

</TEXT>

