<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   North `Likely' To React to IAEA Demand 14 Jan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1301232094 Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network in Korean 2215 GMT 13 
Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> SK1301232094 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Korean </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Cha Man-sun from Vienna] </F>
  [Text] North Korea is likely to respond on 14 January to 
the IAEA checklist that was delivered to the North on 10 January 
for inspection of the seven nuclear facilities [haek sisol]. 
  On 13 January, Yun Ho-chin, counselor of the North Korean 
Embassy in Vienna, who is the chief North Korean delegate to 
working-level contacts with the IAEA, said that North Korea 
would respond to the IAEA demand soon and that its response was 
delayed because there were many things to review carefully due 
to differences in basic positions [kibonjogin ipchang chairo] 
between North Korea and the IAEA. 
  He also hinted that North Korea will not completely meet the 
IAEA demand despite an agreement with the United States, 
stressing that there is no change in their position that the 
nuclear issue should be resolved through negotiations between 
North Korea and the United States. 

</TEXT>

