<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   MITI Minister Rejects New `Quad' Trade Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1401025894 Tokyo KYODO in English 0238 GMT 14 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1401025894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 14 KYODO -- Japanese Trade Minister 
Hiroshi Kumagai ruled out Friday [14 January] a new round of 
quadrilateral ministerial trade talks on market access under the 
General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (GATT). 
  Kumagai, minister of international trade and industry, made 
the remark in response to recent news reports that the United 
States and the European Union (EU) have agreed to call for 
ministerial talks among the four trading partners of Canada, the 
EU, Japan and the U.S. next month. 
  "There is no possibility of a new round of talks since 
negotiations have already been concluded," he said. 
  Working-level talks will be enough if they want to confirm 
agreements reached under the GATT negotiations, he added. 
  Kumagai also said no ministerial talks are required for 
Japan 
and the U.S. at this stage to break an impasse in their talks on 
a "framework" for bilateral trade. 
  U.S. Trade Representative Mickey Kantor suggested both sides 
hold high-level talks to straighten out differences. 
  The two parties should continue negotiations strenuously, 
rather than setting the stage for higher-level talks, he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

