<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Thais, Chinese Accused of Illegal Entry </TI></H3>
<H4>   Suspended Sentences for Chinese </H4>
<F P=102> OW1301131794 Tokyo KYODO in English 1202 GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1301131794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Wakayama, Jan. 13 KYODO -- The Wakayama District 
Court on Thursday [13 January] sentenced 26 Chinese accused of 
illegally entering Japan to eight months in prison with the 
sentences suspended for three years. 
  The 26 Chinese were the first group to be sentenced among 78 
people from China's coastal province of Fujian who were charged 
with illegally entering Japan. 
  Presiding Judge Yoshimichi Takigawa handed down suspended 
sentences, saying there was room for sympathy although they 
entered Japan for the purpose of working illegally in the 
country. Prosecutors had demanded prison terms of eight months. 
  The 78 Chinese were among a group of 104 who arrived in 
Shirahama, Wakayama Prefecture, on November 22 aboard a 
Taiwanese-registered fishing vessel. 
  Prosecutors did not charge the seven crew members and 19 
other Chinese were not indicted because they are minors. 
  The group left China on November 8 after paying about 30,000 
renminbi (about 400,000 yen) to Chinese brokers. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

