<H3> <TI>   Fujii Discusses Stimulus Package </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2001054394 Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database in Japanese 20 
Jan 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2001054394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 20 Jan 94 Morning </F>
Edition] 
  [Text] The coalition government plans to map out an 
additional package of stimulus measures next week. Commenting 
on the question of whether the stimulus package includes the 
income tax reduction, Finance Minister Hirohisa Fujii told a 
news conference on the evening of 19 January: "The Economic 
Consultative Council (chaired by Tsutomu Hata, deputy prime 
minister and foreign minister) of the ruling parties will be 
asked to discuss the question. In my view, it is desirable that 
the additional package of stimulus measures include the income 
tax reduction." As for the question of how to make up for a 
fiscal shortfall incurring from cuts in the income tax, Mr. 
Fujii said: "I think the council also will be asked to discuss 
the question." Asked to comment on reports that Japan-U.S. 
finance ministerial talks would be held on 23 January, the 
finance minister said: "Although there has been no formal 
request for the talks from the United States, I will have to 
positively consider holding the talks if the United States makes 
such a request." 
  Asked about the future of political reform at the news 
conference, the finance minister declined to specifically 
mention a schedule for carrying out the political reform, 
saying: "I am not in a position to predict how the political 
reform will be carried out in the future." Referring again to 
the additional package of stimulus measures, Mr. Fujii said: 
"Now, government ministries, especially the Economic Planning 
Agency, are working on the package and substantial progress has 
been made. I think that they will map out the package before 
long." At the news conference, he repeated his view that the 
Economic Consultative Council will discuss ways in detail for 
the income tax reduction. 
  On the Japan-U.S. finance ministerial talks, Mr. Fujii said 
the United States had not formally sounded out Japan about 
holding the talks, but added: "I understand that Treasury 
Secretary Bentsen will stop in a Tokyo suburb for his plane's 
refueling on 23 January on his way back to Washington from his 
visit to China." 

</TEXT>

