<H3> <TI>   Kumagai Hints at Large Increase in Public Works </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1701015194 Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database in Japanese 17 
Jan 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1701015194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From MAINICHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 17 January Morning </F>
Edition] 
  [Text] Shinseito [Japan Renewal Party] held a ceremony to 
mark the formation of its Nagaoka Chapter in Nagaoka City, 
Niigate Prefecture, on 16 January. Speaking at the ceremony, 
Hiroshi Kumagai, Ministry of International Trade and Industry 
[MITI] minister, touched on the "Basic Plan for Public 
Investment" that has been taken up for discussion at the 
Japan-U.S. economic framework talks and said: "Japan has 
promised the world that it will spend 430 trillion yen for 
public works projects by the year 2000, and the Japanese 
Government has moved up their implementation. The government is 
now studying the possibility of spending an additional 100 
trillion yen for the public works projects." In this way, Mr. 
Kumagai made it clear that the government plans to drastically 
increase the budget for public works projects. Referring to the 
Japan's economic growth rate, Mr. Kumagai said: "About 3 percent 
is compatible with the potentiality of the Japanese economy. 
The government is studying the possibility of adopting a policy 
to attain a 3-percent growth rate next year." 

</TEXT>

