<F P=101> Mongolia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ochirbat Interviewed on Constitution Anniversary </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1401210394 Ulaanbaatar MONTSAME in English 1901 GMT 14 Jan 
94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1401210394 </F>
<F P=104>  Ulaanbaatar MONTSAME </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Ulaanbaatar, January 14 (OANA-MONTSAME) -- The 
president of Mongolia P. Ochirbat answered questions of a 
correspondent of the newspaper ARDIYN ERH on the occasion of the 
second anniversary of adoption of the new Constitution of 
Mongolia. 
  As the president announced, the new Constitution has legally 
consolidated achievements in democratization and renewal of the 
country, has become a legal basis for ensuring the state 
sovereignty, the human rights and freedoms, formation of the new 
state system, transition of the country to market economic 
relations. The Constitution, stressed P. Ochirbat, ensures 
national consent in solution of difficult tasks at the first 
stage of foundation in the country of a humane, democratic civil 
society. The president notes that in the past two years a big 
work was done on realization of provisions of the Constitution, 
including on legal consolidation of a legal basis for 
organization and activity of the state organs. The president 
calls the State Great Hural, the government and other organs to 
work actively for further intensification of the renewal 
processes in accordance with ideas of the Constitution. 
  In the president's view, for the present it is early to 
speak 
about changing of certain provisions of the Constitution, about 
which talks are going on. The main thing, stressed the 
president, is a complete realization and observation of the 
basic law. In this connection President P. Ochirbat pointed out 
to the necessity of combining efforts of scientists for 
interpretation of provisions of the Constitution. 
  The president does not deny a possibility of perfection in 
future of certain provisions of the Constitution, and expresses 
a confidence that its basic ideas will remain unchanged. 

</TEXT>

