<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Mongolia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Security Chief Rejects `Political Police' Role </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1401210494 Ulaanbaatar MONTSAME in English 1854 GMT 14 Jan 
94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1401210494 </F>
<F P=104>  Ulaanbaatar MONTSAME </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Ulaanbaatar, January 14 (OANA-MONTSAME) -- The 
state security organs should not play a role of political 
police, announces the new chief of the State Security Central 
Department, Lieutenant Colonel D. Sandag in interview with 
correspondent of the newspaper ARDIYN ERH. D. Sandag notes that 
the functions of the department are intelligence and 
counterintelligence work, the state guarding. The department 
should not be engaged in other activity, except the mentioned 
functions, says D. Sandag. He considers expedient to revise the 
law on state security organs, which was adopted in 1992. 
  This law, he notes, was based on the old structures, methods 
and forms. Of activity of the previous state security organs, 
D. Sandag considers as necessary promotion of young people, the 
raising of their qualification. 
  Answering questions of the correspondent, D. Sandag stresses 
that those working at state security organs as military 
servicemen should observe a strict discipline, abstain from 
belonging to any party, as it is envisaged by the law. In this 
sense, he says, forces in opposition should not exist in state 
security organs. 
  Concerning the statement by Colonel L. Sanjaasuren on 
intentions to liquidate the materials about abuse of power and 
bribery by some high officials, which are kept in the State 
Security Department, D. Sandag notes that, in his view, such 
serious violations do not exist, and that the accusations 
brought might be based on a striving for winning authority, by 
using the differences of political forces. D. Sandag notes that 
the issues, which were touched upon by Colonel L. Sanjaasuren, 
are being now checked up by a special commission of the 
parliament and the public will be get acquainted with results in 
its time [sentence as received]. In D. Sandag's view, the 
recent changes of the leadership of the State Security Central 
Department have been connected with shortcomings in their 
activity. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

