<H3> <TI>   `Russian Specialists' Estimate Uranium Reserves </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1401212394 Ulaanbaatar MONTSAME in English 1907 GMT 14 Jan 
94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1401212394 </F>
<F P=104>  Ulaanbaatar MONTSAME </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Ulaanbaatar, January 14 (OANA-MONTSAME) -- 
"According to the prognosis of the Russian specialists our 
country has uranic ore reserves worth of 1.5 million tons. This 
is not a small figure and Mongolia needs to appear on the world 
market. Jointly with Russia and the U.S.A. we will exploit the 
Haraat deposit in Dundgobi Aymag. Prospecting works will start 
from this year," said the general director of the Geological 
Research Department of the Ministry of Geology and Mineral 
Resources of Mongolia G. Jamsrandorj [spelling as received]. He 
refuted the rumours about taking on a long-term lease by Russia 
of the Mardai [spelling as received] uranic ore deposit as a 
compensation of the external debt of Mongolia and said that the 
issues are being discussed about changing the terms of the 
earlier signed agreements and that the sides agreed in principle 
of foundation of a joint enterprise. 
  According G. Jamsrandorj, prices of uranic ore on the world 
market will start increasing in 5-7 years, as in the 21st 
century atomic energy will become a basic source of electric 
energy in the world. Taking this into consideration, the 
ministry has founded an independent company "Uranium" for 
establishment of contacts with the World Nuclear Energy Agency 
[title as received], well-known companies, exploration of 
opportunities to appear on the world uranic ore market. In 
general, the Mongols should dispose themselves their uranium 
[sentence as received]. 
  At the recent sitting of the National Security Council of 
Mongolia considered was a report of the Ministry of Geology on 
the state of geological prospecting and exploitation of the 
uranic ore deposits, perspectives for this sphere, foundation of 
joint enterprises, opportunities for appearing on the world 
market, and ecological issues. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

